    \rulename{app-fun-wrong-l} & |applyx wrong v| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{app-fun-wrong-b} & |applyx wrong wrong| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{choice-wrong-l} & |wrong choice v| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{choice-wrong-b} & |wrong choice wrong| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{one-wrong} & |one wrong| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{all-wrong} & |all (v_1 choice dots v_n choice wrong)| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{succeeds-fail} & |succeeds fail| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{succeeds-choice} & |succeeds (v choice e)| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
    \rulename{succeeds-wrong} & |succeeds wrong| & \movesto & |wrong| \\
     \end{array}
   \end{array}
   $$
\caption{The Verse calculus: axioms for |wrong|} \label{fig:wrong-axioms}
\end{figurebox}


\subsection{Expressions and values}

An expression |e| has syntax given in \Cref{fig:verse-syntax}.
Constants |k| are simply integers in this presentation, and come equipped with
some primitive operations.  To avoid clutter, we provide only two representative
operations, |add| for integer addition, and |gt| for integer comparison.

\paragraph{Tuples and arrays.}
All functions (including |add| and |gt|) take a single argument, but that
argument can be a tuple, say |(e_1,e_2)|. In Verse, tuples and arrays are the same data structure;
a tuple is just an array whose size is statically known.
The expression |(e_1, dots, e_n)| builds an $n$-ary tuple, while |for| constructs an array.
We discuss |for| in \Cref{sec:for}.
\joachim{Note that our syntax requires tuples to be in A-Normal-Form. We should explain that here. Also, if we require tuples construction in ANF, why not function application.}

\paragraph{Unification and sequencing.}
Unification and sequencing are part of the expressions language.
They are written |(e_1 == e_2)| and |(e_1; e_2)| respectively.
Both of these operators are associative.

\paragraph{Lambda and application.}  Lambda abstractions are written |(x => e)|, and are applied
 as usual |applyx e_1 e_2|.

\paragraph{Recursion}
Recursion is encoded as a special fixpoint operator |rec f e|, with the meaning that |rec f e == fix (f => e)|.
\joachim{Out of curiosity: Why this? Could we use |fix v| instead, with |applyx (fix v) e| $\movesto$ |applyx (applyx v (fix v)) e|? Or could we even make |fix| a primitive operation, with |fix(v)| $\movesto$ |applyx v (fix v)|? (I guess the latter isn't good because we want |fix f| to be a value)}
\lennart{No deep reason.  I thought this looked nicer.}

\paragraph{Choice.}
In Verse, an expression may yield a sequence of zero, one, or many results.  The expression |fail| yields
zero results; the expression |(e_1 choice e_2)| yields all the results of |e_1| and then all the results
of |e_2|.  The choice operator is associative.

\paragraph{Values.}
A value |v| can be a variable |x|, or it can be a head-normal form |hnf|.
The latter is just an integer constant |k|, an array |(v_1, dots,v_n)|, lambda |(x => e)|,
or a recursive definition |rec f e|.

\subsection{\Hexp{}s and heaps}

\joachim{This whole section is out-of-date with defs no longer containing bindings.}

A \hexp{} has the form |(def h e)|, where |h| is a \emph{heap}, whose syntax is given in
\Cref{fig:verse-syntax}.  A heap is just a collection of \emph{bindings}, which take one of two forms:
\begin{itemize}
\item A binding |x| simply introduces the variable |x|, without giving it a value.
\item A binding |x:=v| binds the variable |x| to the value |v|.
\end{itemize}
These heaps play the role of |let| expressions in the call by need lambda calculus (\Cref{sec:call-by-need}).

A particular heap has at most one binding for a variable |x|.
When a heap is born, all its bindings are variable introductions |x|; as execution progresses some of
these variables get a value |x:=v|.  Once a variable gets value, that value never changes: it is immutable.

A binding in a heap may refer to another binding (e.g |x:=y| or |x:=(y,2)|); but the bindings are never recursive.
Here are some example heaps, with an indication of whether they are well formed:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{rl}
  Heap, $h$ & OK or not? \\
  \hline
  |(x:=1, y)| & OK \\
  |(x:=1, y:=2)| & OK \\
  |(x:=y, y:=2)| & OK \\
  |(x:=(1,x))|   & Not OK: recursive \\
  |(x:=(y1,y2), y1, y2:=4)| & OK \\
  |(x:=add^(1,2))| & Syntactically invalid; only values are allowed \\
  |(f:= n => f(n)| & Not OK: recursive \\
  |(f:= rec g (n => g(n)))| & OK \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection{|wrong|}
Expressions that make no sense reduce to |wrong|, e.g., using a number as a function in a function application.
There are no general reduction rules to propagate |wrong|, instead the reduction gets stuck.
\joachim{I'm a bit confused, there are a few incomplete rules to propagate wrong in \ref{fig:wrong-axioms}. In particular, I'd be curious about |fail; wrong|. But also about |if v choice wrong|. }
\lennart{We need to think more about |wrong|.  You can make case for |fail; wrong| being |fail|.
  Consider |int[x]; x+1|, if the type test fails we don't care about |x+1|.}
\lennart{We can remove the axioms that propagate |wrong| at all.  I just put those two in, because they don't interfere with |fail|.}

\joachim{Also, due to \rulename{fail}, we have |wrong; fail| $\movesto$ |fail|, that does not look right. Probably |e;X| should not be an execution context.}
\lennart{No, |e;X| must be an execution context.  Consider |def x (x+1; x = 2)|, we must do the |x = 2| before we can do |x+1|.}

An alternative to using |wrong| would be to say that bad expressions just get stuck.
Unfortunately this leads to non-confluence as we can get stuck in different way depending on the order of reduction.
A simple example of this is \\
|def x (x=(()=>1); x=(()=>2); x())| \\
This can be reduced by \rulename{bind} in two different ways, and after a few more reduction we get stuck with
either \\
|(()=>1)=(()=>2); 1| \\
or\\
|(()=>2)=(()=>1); 2| \\
So even if we consider terms modulo commutativity of equality we have different terms.

\subsection{Confluence}
We have the following conjecture: the Verse reduction rules are confluent in the following sense.
\begin{quote}
  Using the reduction rules repeatedly will
  \begin{itemize}
  \item terminate with a term in |hnf|.  This is a successful evaluation.
  \item terminate without a term in |hnf|, i.e., get stuck.
  \item not terminate.
  \end{itemize}
  All successful evaluations will produce the same |hnf| (up to $\alpha,\beta$-equivalence?).
\end{quote}

\subsection{Evaluation strategy}
The axioms given in figures \ref{fig:general-axioms} and \ref{fig:unification-axioms}
can be used anywhere in a program.
This is similar to how the axioms for the $\lambda$-calculus in figure \ref{fig:call-by-name} can be applied anywhere.
In figure \ref{fig:verse-eval} we introduce an evaluation context |E| to force a particular evaluation order.

We would like to have a similar |E| for Verse, but it seems difficult to find one that always identifies a
unique redex for the next reduction.
Instead we settle for an evaluation context that is ambiguous and allows many different redexes, figure \ref{fig:verse-eval}.
It allows evaluation almost everywhere, with exception of under a $\lambda$.
The reason to disallow this is that we do not know if they are needed.
